    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **James Wood** (76.28) and **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) headline our production expectations as our strongest plays. **James Wood** benefits from a massive 19% SP skill boost against Mart\u00edn P\u00e9rez, and hitting out of the leadoff spot provides optimal run-scoring leverage. **Mickey Moniak** is in a premier position to capitalize on Walker Buehler\u2019s high 5.19 xERA; the park factors in his favor, coupled with the slow SP delivery that signals high stolen base probability, make him a locked-in high-upside asset. **Vinnie Pasquantino** also warrants a mention for his 68.43 score, driven by a favorable 14% platoon edge against Chris Bassitt and wind conditions blowing out, which should provide a solid floor for our R/RBI categories.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision today was leaving **Kyle Karros** (61.99) on the bench. While his score is technically higher than several starters\u2014including **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** (53.84) and **Corbin Carroll** (53.11)\u2014the optimizer prioritized the elite speed and stolen base utility provided by the rest of the outfield and MI group to maintain our competitive edge in the scarcest category. **Corbin Carroll** in particular represents a risk, as his score is depressed to 53.11 due to a tough matchup against Anthony Kay (2.60 xERA). However, we are playing for the high-end talent variance there. We continue to monitor the \"Lineup Pending\" status for all starters, especially **Luis Campusano** and **Dalton Rushing**, whose efficiency relies heavily on their finalized spot in the order; any move down the lineup will naturally erode their base projections and potentially impact our daily cap management.",
